ricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is about recurrent functions of applicative morphology not included in typologically-oriented definitions. Based on substantial cross-linguistic evidence, it challenges received wisdom on applicatives in several ways. First, in many of the surveyed languages, applicatives are the sole means to introduce a non-Actor semantic role into a clause. When there is an alternative way of expression, the applicative counterpart often has no valence-increasing effect on the targeted root. Second, applicative morphology can introduce constituents which are not syntactic objects and/or co-occur with obliques. Third, functions such as conveying aspectual nuances to the predicate (intensity, repetition, habituality) or its arguments (partitive P, highly individuated P), narrow-focusing constituents, and functioning as category-changing devices are attested in geographically distant and genetically unrelated languages. Further, this volume reveals that spatial-related morphology is prone to developing applicative functions in disparate languages and phyla. Finally, several contributions discuss the diachrony of applicative constructions and their (non-syntactic) attested functions, including a case of applicatives-in-the-making.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aMorphologie. 4aPragmatik. 4aSemantik.  aLanguage Change.  aSemantic and Pragmatic Functions.  aSpatial Morphology.  aValence-Neutral Applicative Morphology.1 aEvans, Bethwyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerrero, Lilián, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunnink, Hilde, econtr